The Presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V. and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reached its climax with the ceremony in which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He receives this as the fourth US President, but only as the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghanistan war when the prize is taken over.
The President does not wish to escape this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a President who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he strengthened his efforts by sending other troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony Obama also received the Golmedaille, the diploma and the check over ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete caritative work.
The event program then provides a banquet with the president and his wife, where, apart from Norway's king and queen, the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests will be present.
Obama was very reluctant about the price from the beginning.
For example, he suggested that he felt that he did not quite deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that it is not only the price for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this was "call for action" for him.
