Czech discovery: a substance that also affects “steeled” HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the link to normal virus variants does not work as much as one of the existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, the patient can prolong the medicine collection and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, which are no longer effective.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, of the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and of the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with the virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances called metalocarborane have an effect on the protein substance responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral proliferation in ways other than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new 'improved' compounds, which were prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-ply cages, consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Domestic and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein substance of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would occur.
If we switch off HIV protease, we also disable the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in the press report, published by the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effects of this series of substances against HIV protease were tested in the test tube, also against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its further properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formations, makes metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective anti-HIV medicinal products, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory for Structural Biology of the Institutes for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and of the Institute for Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
