Can Islam Be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted for a ban on minarette construction and the concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of the most declared secularized societies in Europe — and integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French do not love headscarves" (original title: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves") (2006), an elegant and highly argumentative study of a dispute that shared and occupied the country over a decade and a half and its effects are still to be seen today.
Bowen's latest book offers a more comprehensive and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what really happens in this area.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it "Islamic Spaces".
He's a good listener, he's giving back debates between teachers and students on the questions they're most worried about.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and the rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-oriented banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profanal matters, he claims, which make up daily life, quite unlike the political dramas that the media employ.
The author recognizes a new generation of Imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They don't have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who questioned Bowen are mostly in disagreement with their salafi counterparts – defenders of purist Sunni Islam, which is linked to Saudi Arabia – who nowadays show a small but influential presence among European Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions to what extent French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who so passionately guard the separation of Church and State) really feel obliged to pluralism.
He indicates that Muslims may have experienced harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes a "enhancement of the screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
