The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle curls and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived some 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was located at the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation they gathered the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories on Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaurier fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually you will find only single fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching, the dinosaurs first appeared some 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these ur-dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts debated when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, known as the "long necks", the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants eating Ornithischia (Vogelbeckensaurier), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, such as the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America across all the continents, which were still a single land mass at that time as a supercontinent Pangaga.
The fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot stem from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonner Palæontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be distorted because in South America just a lot of primitive Dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant farm animals of the Middle Ages, it is still puzzling.
During the trias the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying auras and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border between the trias and the Jura died out.
Success Story Did Not Last Forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals helped to flower, which had also developed in the Trias and since then caused a shadow: the mammals.
