Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-lock braking system ABS at the time and as with the stability control ESP at the moment, the auxiliary braking systems must become mandatory in European cars in case of an emergency.
In fact, they are already required for all newly registered passenger cars and light small carriers, for which the remaining vehicles have been set a standstill period by the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many road accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake manoeuvre, which detects the system on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake strength applied by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to hit the brake pedal before the crash, and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
By contrast, the braking aid intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance travelled by a car during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even less accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
