New Vehicle Review Programmes
In these days of storms and accidents not only do the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged to the workshops where an assessor has to assess the damage caused and the cost of the repair.
No accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and hours of work can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and working hours, may take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest information technology tools, it is a matter of minutes
Therefore, almost 100% of the assessors use this kind of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process them afterwards and to offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reports are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing with the tool market for review and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data the manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Director of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is becoming increasingly large, up to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and motorizations have been on the market than in the last fifteen years.
As soon as a new car enters the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, for each of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catagolated and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold model, work can be completed in a week if the procedure is speedy.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the road-traffic vehicle fleet, it is over 99%.
In order to carry out the documentation work and to produce databases, Audatex has eight centres distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each one of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every second day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating the error or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain but in the United States.
With the transparency of the products that Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the kind of support it gives to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products AudaPlus, a standard solution for the assessment of accidents for the assessors.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times or paint prices estimated by the manufacturer.
This tool is paid depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each opinion.
It is most expensive for customers who rarely use it at most ten times a month, namely 5.75 Euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that produces thousands of opinions negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly belt, using the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle discs, and AudaSubastas is an open service on the Internet for the specialist market, with which you can offer vehicles that have been declared total damage.
Your statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, carrying out geodemographic analyses or in obtaining information on the variations by brand and model.
For example, one can examine how many models of a particular car brand had to be involved in the workshop due to boilers or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to developing this kind of computer tools.
It distributes among others Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and provides digital images of the same kind, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is an Eina Group company founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for assessing vehicle damage, breakdowns and maintenance.
The GT expert leader is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3.100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has increased by 20% annually over the last three years and in 2008 sales amounted to EUR 10.8 million.
At the beginning of last year they began to go on the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the sources of the company, 62% of its business is in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
The total turnover in the world of the group Solera (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounts to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
The company has revenue of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at a value of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the reference index Standard & Poor's.
